    "engine": "jupyter",
    "markdown": "---\ntitle: \"Neurosymbolic solver for deductive trading\"\njupyter: brainvomit\nexecute:\n  echo: false\n  warning: false\n---\n\n## Thesis\n\nA prediction market sells **contracts** that pay \\$1 if a stated thing happens and\n\\$0 if it doesn't, so a contract's price acts like the crowd's estimate of the\nprobability. The familiar ways to make risk-free money here — prices that don't add\nup, or the same bet priced differently on two sites — vanish fast once professional\ntraders arrive, leaving a race won by whoever is fastest.\n\nThis project tests a different kind of opportunity: one you find by **reasoning**,\nnot by being fast. Every contract has a **rulebook** — the precise legal text that\ndecides payout. The plan: use a language model to read those rulebooks and translate\nthem into formal logic, then hand that logic to an automated theorem-prover (a\n**solver**) that can *prove* when two or more contracts' prices logically\ncontradict each other. A proven contradiction is a guaranteed-profit trade. The edge,\nif it exists, comes from reading fine print nobody bothered to combine — not from\ntrading faster.\n\n<!-- TODO: your framing / why this caught your interest. -->\n\nTwo things had to arrive together: **markets that trade yes/no claims** (logic needs\ntrue/false statements to work on), and **cheap reading of dense legal text** (turning\nexception-riddled fine print into clean structure used to take a human per contract;\nlanguage models made it cheap at scale).\n\n**Induction** learns patterns from data (\"it went up the last ten times\") — what\nessentially all quantitative trading does. **Deduction** proves something *must*\nfollow from rules (\"if one party controls the House, the Speaker is necessarily from\nthat party\"). Prediction markets are the first asset class where deduction bites,\nbecause they trade true/false claims that can logically depend on one another.\n\nThere's also a reason we *must* stay with deduction: a market event happens once, and\nfor a one-time event a single \"true probability\" is ill-defined. What *is* well-defined\nis **coherence** — whether a set of prices contradict each other right now. That can be\nchecked today, predicting nothing. Trust comes from a **division of labor**: the\nlanguage model does only the fuzzy part (reading and translating); everything with a\nprovably-correct answer goes to the solver.\n\n<!-- TODO. -->\n\n## Strategy\n\nThe expensive step — carefully reading a rulebook, turning it into logic, checking it\nwith the solver — is spent only on promising candidates, picked out by cheap filters\nfirst. The pipeline:\n\n> is it actually being traded? → translate rulebooks into logic → is the link\n> *enforceable* (forced by the rules, not just true about the world)? → score how much\n> the contracts pin each other down → grow the set toward whatever adds the most force\n\nTwo ideas do the heavy lifting. A **grounding** label attached to every claimed link\nnames *what* connects two contracts — which makes \"merely true about the world\" links\nimpossible to write down, and checks the resolver is actually obligated to honor the\nlink at payout. And the **force score** counts how many still-possible outcomes a\ncontract rules out, a set-level measure that can catch a link only visible when three\nor more contracts combine.\n\nWhether a search is even worth starting is decided up front by a break-even rule —\nthe fraction of groups that must contain a tradeable find to justify the cost:\n\n$$p_1 = \\frac{C_\\text{cluster}}{V_\\text{find}\\times R}$$\n\nwhere $C_\\text{cluster}$ is the cost to examine one group, $V_\\text{find}$ the profit\nper find (capped by how much the market can absorb), and $R$ how many times one\ndiscovery pays off.\n\n<!-- TODO: anything you want to draw out about the architecture. -->\n\n## The golden case\n\nThe relationship has to be **forced by the rulebooks** (not the casual descriptions),\n**true no matter how the world turns out**, **hidden across contracts** (visible only\nby reading two or more together), **honored at payout** (same resolver, same rules),\nand **contradicted by the actual tradeable prices** — with real volume on every leg at\nonce. Conditions about history, outside copies, and the crowd all collapse into one\nquestion: **does anyone already watch this relationship here?** If yes, it's priced.\nSo the target is one *nobody* watches — which makes any such opportunity temporary.\n\n<!-- TODO: why a continuous strike destroys the forced link. -->\n\n## Findings\n\n### 1. Single contracts — dead end\n\nIn a 20-contract sample, about half had a gap between headline and fine print; **none\nwere tradeable** (each gap was harmless or already priced). Reading one contract is\neasy, so the edge is gone.\n\n<!-- TODO. -->\n\n### 2. Economics & finance — almost certainly dead\n\nNearly every economics/finance contract also trades elsewhere (rate futures, yields,\nofficial series), where professionals keep it priced — the **outside-copy killer**.\nSorting the catalog by \"does an outside copy exist?\":\n\n::: {#cell-setup .cell execution_count=1}\n\n::: {#setup .cell-output .cell-output-display}\n```{=html}\n<div>            <script src=\"https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/mathjax/2.7.5/MathJax.js?config=TeX-AMS-MML_SVG\"></script><script type=\"text/javascript\">if (window.MathJax && window.MathJax.Hub && window.MathJax.Hub.Config) {window.MathJax.Hub.Config({SVG: {font: \"STIX-Web\"}});}</script>                <script type=\"text/javascript\">window.PlotlyConfig = {MathJaxConfig: 'local'};</script>\n        <script charset=\"utf-8\" src=\"https://cdn.plot.ly/plotly-3.0.1.min.js\"></script>                <div id=\"6763f169-afa6-44cf-ab69-c18c643447c7\" class=\"plotly-graph-div\" style=\"height:460px; width:100%;\"></div>            <script type=\"text/javascript\">                window.PLOTLYENV=window.PLOTLYENV || {};                                if (documen