erolinewidth\":2},\"yaxis\":{\"gridcolor\":\"white\",\"linecolor\":\"white\",\"ticks\":\"\",\"title\":{\"standoff\":15},\"zerolinecolor\":\"white\",\"automargin\":true,\"zerolinewidth\":2},\"scene\":{\"xaxis\":{\"backgroundcolor\":\"#E5ECF6\",\"gridcolor\":\"white\",\"linecolor\":\"white\",\"showbackground\":true,\"ticks\":\"\",\"zerolinecolor\":\"white\",\"gridwidth\":2},\"yaxis\":{\"backgroundcolor\":\"#E5ECF6\",\"gridcolor\":\"white\",\"linecolor\":\"white\",\"showbackground\":true,\"ticks\":\"\",\"zerolinecolor\":\"white\",\"gridwidth\":2},\"zaxis\":{\"backgroundcolor\":\"#E5ECF6\",\"gridcolor\":\"white\",\"linecolor\":\"white\",\"showbackground\":true,\"ticks\":\"\",\"zerolinecolor\":\"white\",\"gridwidth\":2}},\"shapedefaults\":{\"line\":{\"color\":\"#2a3f5f\"}},\"annotationdefaults\":{\"arrowcolor\":\"#2a3f5f\",\"arrowhead\":0,\"arrowwidth\":1},\"geo\":{\"bgcolor\":\"white\",\"landcolor\":\"#E5ECF6\",\"subunitcolor\":\"white\",\"showland\":true,\"showlakes\":true,\"lakecolor\":\"white\"},\"title\":{\"x\":0.05},\"mapbox\":{\"style\":\"light\"},\"margin\":{\"b\":0,\"l\":0,\"r\":0,\"t\":30}}},\"xaxis\":{\"anchor\":\"y\",\"domain\":[0.0,1.0],\"title\":{\"text\":\"fraction\"}},\"yaxis\":{\"anchor\":\"x\",\"domain\":[0.0,1.0],\"title\":{\"text\":\"\"}},\"legend\":{\"title\":{\"text\":\"kind\"},\"tracegroupgap\":0,\"orientation\":\"h\",\"y\":1.06},\"barmode\":\"stack\",\"height\":440,\"margin\":{\"l\":0,\"r\":0,\"t\":10,\"b\":0}},                        {\"responsive\": true}                    ).then(function(){\n                            \nvar gd = document.getElementById('c120c163-6b78-4988-bd19-5e415d8109ca');\nvar x = new MutationObserver(function (mutations, observer) {{\n        var display = window.getComputedStyle(gd).display;\n        if (!display || display === 'none') {{\n            console.log([gd, 'removed!']);\n            Plotly.purge(gd);\n            observer.disconnect();\n        }}\n}});\n\n// Listen for the removal of the full notebook cells\nvar notebookContainer = gd.closest('#notebook-container');\nif (notebookContainer) {{\n    x.observe(notebookContainer, {childList: true});\n}}\n\n// Listen for the clearing of the current output cell\nvar outputEl = gd.closest('.output');\nif (outputEl) {{\n    x.observe(outputEl, {childList: true});\n}}\n\n                        })                };            </script>        </div>\n```\n:::\n:::\n\n\n<!-- TODO: caution — \"many contracts per event\" is not \"logically linked.\" -->\n\n### 5. Sports — good structure, killed by other exchanges\n\nSports has the best raw structure (many related yes/no bets on one game) and dodges\nthe continuous-number trap — but every bet also exists at a sportsbook, which keeps\nthe set priced. *Sports is economics with a yes/no coat of paint.* No category has\n\"native + hidden + recurring\" all at once, so the target is a rare specific **pair** of\ncontracts, not a whole category.\n\n<!-- TODO. -->\n\n### 6. The narrowed hunt — AI-model rankings\n\nA targeted search surfaced two AI-model-ranking series off the same leaderboard, one\nframed **by company** and one **by model**, with the obvious link \"a company's chance\nis the sum of its models' chances.\" It failed three predicted ways: the prices already\nagreed within the spread; the same crowd traded both framings; and the two lists didn't\nline up cleanly. *Lesson: different framing only helps if it attracts two genuinely\ndifferent crowds.*\n\n<!-- TODO. -->\n\n### 7. The life and death of a real arbitrage\n\nThe strongest find: a **bundled bet on which party wins the House Speakership** equals\na **direct bet on which party controls the House**, split into the two cases of who\ncontrols the Senate. It clears every earlier hurdle — logically forced, decided by one\nauthority, framed two very different ways, watched by two different crowds, every leg\nheavily traded — and it was genuinely incoherent:\n\n| | value |\n| --- | --- |\n| Bundle implies P(party controls House) | **76%** |\n| Direct contract bid | **78%** |\n| Gross logical gap | **2¢** |\n| Open interest across the three legs | \\$4.1M / \\$990k / \\$850k, ~1¢ spreads |\n| Exchange fee across three legs | ~**4.5¢** |\n| **Net** | **≈ −2.5¢** per contract |\n\nThe squeeze: liquid legs mean a tiny gap, and the per-leg fee is bigger than the gap. A\n*large* gap would need a badly-priced leg — but that's either barely traded (can't\ntrade it) or merely slow to update (a speed edge, not a logic edge).\n\n<!-- TODO: the careful conclusion — real mispricings exist, but the profitable middle\nis squeezed from both sides. -->\n\n## Summary\n### The golden rules\n\n- **Continuous number vs. yes/no — the master heuristic.** A forced link between\n  contracts survives only when the contracts resolve on **yes/no events** (a law\n  passed, a person appointed) and breaks when they resolve on a **continuous number**\n  (a vote share, an inflation reading). *Found:* it was the one test that kept\n  deciding the \"holds no matter what else happens\" condition across every category\n  scored. *Why:* a continuous strike makes the exact number the operative fact, so for\n  some values the clean implication between two contracts simply fails; a yes/no fact\n  is shared verbatim, so the implication is automatic.\n- **\"Does anyone already watch this relationship here?\" — the one question that\n  matters.** The three venue/timing conditions (a price history exists, an outside\n  copy exists, a sharp local crowd does the logic) collapse into this single test.\n  *Why:* a watched relationship is already priced, so the only exploitable link is one\n  nobody watches — which also means **any edge is temporary**, closing the moment\n  attention arrives.\n- **The outside-copy killer dominates everything.** *Found:* sorting the ~11k contract\n  families by \"does an external market price the same bet?\" splits them ~3,674 dead\n  (Sports 2,221, Economics 572, Financials 568, Crypto 253, Commodities 60) vs. ~7,287\n  native-to-Kalshi. *Why:* wherever the same exposure trades elsewhere (a future, a\n  sportsbook line, a terminal), professionals keep *that* market coherent and the\n  correct price flows back to Kalshi.\n\n  — the real target is a *definitional link between different measurements*, which by\n  construction won't appear in a search for identical ones.\n- **Native politics/legal is the fertile ground.** The surface-feature score ranked\n  Entertainment, Politics, Mentions, Sci/Tech on top and Elections, Climate,\n  Economics/Crypto on the bottom — self-consistent with the yes/no rule (the bottom\n  group is dragged down by being number-based and/or outside-copied).\n- **No category has it all; the target is a *pair*.** A usable opportunity needs\n  native + hidden + recurring simultaneously, but every category has at most two of the\n  three (e.g. Sports has structure and yes/no framing but is outside-copied). So the\n  edge is a rare specific *pair of contracts*, not a property of any category — which\n  is why a targeted hand-search beats betting a whole category.\n- **Different framing only helps if it splits the crowd.** The AI-model-ranking pair\n  (company-framed vs. model-framed off one leaderboard) failed because the *same* crowd\n  traded both framings — different labels, one blind spot, no edge.\n\n\n- **A real Kalshi-native mispricing exists.** The House-Speakership bundle equals\n  House-control split by Senate control — logically forced, decided by one authority,\n  framed two very different ways, watched by two different crowds, every leg heavily\n  traded, and genuinely **incoherent** (a bundle-implied 76% against a 78% direct bid,\n  a 2¢ gap). This is the first concrete proof the target class is non-empty.\n- **The fee squeeze — the deepest negative result.** Liquid legs force the gap to be\n  tiny, and the exchange's per-leg taker fee (~4.5¢ across three legs) exceeds it (2¢).\n  A *large* gap would require at least one badly-priced leg — but a badly-priced leg is\n  either barely traded (you can't actually trade it) or merely slow to update (a speed\n  edge, not a logic edge). **The profitable middle is squeezed from both sides.**\n\n\n**Conclusion:** can't quit my day job\n\n<!-- TODO: add/curate the insights you most want to highlight, and your call on next steps. -->\n\n",
